{
  "text": "Prognostic models are complex tools, which can be used to predict clinical outcomes. Many prognostic models which were used for liver cirrhosis have been used to evaluate the ACLF [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The model for end-stage liver disease (MELD) was commonly applied as a prognostic indicator in patients with ACLF. This score is formed from biochemical indicators: international normalized ratio (INR) for assessing coagulopathy, total bilirubin level for assessing liver dysfunction, and the serum creatinine (Cr) concentration as an indicator for assessing renal dysfunction. However, previous study has indicated that serum Cr may not be reliable for assessing the MELD scoring system [CITATION_4] . Cr is an insensitive indicator for assessing acute renal dysfunction since it is highly dependent on extrarenal factors. Serum Cr levels may not change until~50% of renal function has already been lost [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Thus, much more reliable markers for estimation of renal function are required.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "10440305",
